61/* Some of these are #define on some systems, e.g. on AIX to redirect
62 the names to 64bit capable functions for LARGE_FILES support. These
63 redefs are pointless here so we can override them. */

65#undef fopen

68#define fopen(PATH, MODE) fopen_unlocked (PATH, MODE)
69#define fdopen(FILDES, MODE) fdopen_unlocked (FILDES, MODE)
70#define freopen(PATH, MODE, STREAM) freopen_unlocked (PATH, MODE, STREAM)

72/* The compiler is not a multi-threaded application and therefore we
73 do not have to use the locking functions. In fact, using the locking
74 functions can cause the compiler to be significantly slower under
75 I/O bound conditions (such as -g -O0 on very large source files).
76
77 HAVE_DECL_PUTC_UNLOCKED actually indicates whether or not the stdio
78 code is multi-thread safe by default. If it is set to 0, then do
79 not worry about using the _unlocked functions.
80
81 fputs_unlocked, fwrite_unlocked, and fprintf_unlocked are
82 extensions and need to be prototyped by hand (since we do not
83 define _GNU_SOURCE). */
84
85#if defined HAVE_DECL_PUTC_UNLOCKED && HAVE_DECL_PUTC_UNLOCKED
86
87# ifdef HAVE_PUTC_UNLOCKED
88# undef putc
89# define putc(C, Stream) putc_unlocked (C, Stream)
90# endif
91# ifdef HAVE_PUTCHAR_UNLOCKED
92# undef putchar
93# define putchar(C) putchar_unlocked (C)
94# endif
95# ifdef HAVE_GETC_UNLOCKED
96# undef getc
97# define getc(Stream) getc_unlocked (Stream)
98# endif
99# ifdef HAVE_GETCHAR_UNLOCKED
100# undef getchar
101# define getchar() getchar_unlocked ()
102# endif
103# ifdef HAVE_FPUTC_UNLOCKED
104# undef fputc
105# define fputc(C, Stream) fputc_unlocked (C, Stream)
106# endif

314/* A macro to determine whether a VALUE lies inclusively within a
315 certain range without evaluating the VALUE more than once. This
316 macro won't warn if the VALUE is unsigned and the LOWER bound is
317 zero, as it would e.g. with "VALUE >= 0 && ...". Note the LOWER
318 bound *is* evaluated twice, and LOWER must not be greater than
319 UPPER. However the bounds themselves can be either positive or
320 negative. */
321#define IN_RANGE(VALUE, LOWER, UPPER) \
322 ((unsigned HOST_WIDE_INT) (VALUE) - (unsigned HOST_WIDE_INT) (LOWER) \
323 <= (unsigned HOST_WIDE_INT) (UPPER) - (unsigned HOST_WIDE_INT) (LOWER))
324
325/* Infrastructure for defining missing _MAX and _MIN macros. Note that
326 macros defined with these cannot be used in #if. */
327
328/* The extra casts work around common compiler bugs. */
329#define INTTYPE_SIGNED(t) (! ((t) 0 < (t) -1))
330/* The outer cast is needed to work around a bug in Cray C 5.0.3.0.
331 It is necessary at least when t == time_t. */
332#define INTTYPE_MINIMUM(t) ((t) (INTTYPE_SIGNED (t) \
333 ? (t) 1 << (sizeof (t) * CHAR_BIT - 1) : (t) 0))
334#define INTTYPE_MAXIMUM(t) ((t) (~ (t) 0 - INTTYPE_MINIMUM (t)))
335
336/* Use that infrastructure to provide a few constants. */
337#ifndef UCHAR_MAX
338# define UCHAR_MAX INTTYPE_MAXIMUM (unsigned char)
339#endif

392/* Returns the least number N such that N * Y >= X. */
393#define CEIL(x,y) (((x) + (y) - 1) / (y))
394
395/* This macro rounds x up to the y boundary. */
396#define ROUND_UP(x,y) (((x) + (y) - 1) & ~((y) - 1))
397
398/* This macro rounds x down to the y boundary. */
399#define ROUND_DOWN(x,y) ((x) & ~((y) - 1))

737 ((void)(!(EXPR) ? fancy_abort (__FILE__, __LINE__, __FUNCTION__), 0 : 0))
738#elif (GCC_VERSION >= 4005)
739#define gcc_assert(EXPR) \
740 ((void)(__builtin_expect (!(EXPR), 0) ? __builtin_unreachable (), 0 : 0))
741#else
742/* Include EXPR, so that unused variable warnings do not occur. */
743#define gcc_assert(EXPR) ((void)(0 && (EXPR)))
744#endif
745
746#if CHECKING_P
747#define gcc_checking_assert(EXPR) gcc_assert (EXPR)
748#else
749/* N.B.: in release build EXPR is not evaluated. */
750#define gcc_checking_assert(EXPR) ((void)(0 && (EXPR)))
751#endif

1067/* This macro allows casting away const-ness to pass -Wcast-qual
1068 warnings. DO NOT USE THIS UNLESS YOU REALLY HAVE TO! It should
1069 only be used in certain specific cases. One valid case is where
1070 the C standard definitions or prototypes force you to. E.g. if you
1071 need to free a const object, or if you pass a const string to
1072 execv, et al. Another valid use would be in an allocation function
1073 that creates const objects that need to be initialized. In some
1074 cases we have non-const functions that return the argument
1075 (e.g. next_nonnote_insn). Rather than create const shadow
1076 functions, we can cast away const-ness in calling these interfaces
1077 if we're careful to verify that the called function does indeed not
1078 modify its argument and the return value is only used in a const
1079 context. (This can be somewhat dangerous as these assumptions can
1080 change after the fact). Beyond these uses, most other cases of
1081 using this macro should be viewed with extreme caution. */
1082
1083#ifdef __cplusplus
1084#define CONST_CAST2(TOTYPE,FROMTYPE,X) (const_cast<TOTYPE> (X))
1085#else
1086#if defined(__GNUC__) && GCC_VERSION > 4000
1087/* GCC 4.0.x has a bug where it may ICE on this expression,
1088 so does GCC 3.4.x (PR17436). */
1089#define CONST_CAST2(TOTYPE,FROMTYPE,X) ((__extension__(union {FROMTYPE _q; TOTYPE _nq;})(X))._nq)
1090#elif defined(__GNUC__)
1091static inline char *
1092helper_const_non_const_cast (const char *p)
1093{
1094 union {
1095 const char *const_c;
1096 char *c;
1097 } val;
1098 val.const_c = p;
1099 return val.c;
1100}
1101
1102#define CONST_CAST2(TOTYPE,FROMTYPE,X) \
1103 ((TOTYPE) helper_const_non_const_cast ((const char *) (FROMTYPE) (X)))
1104#else
1105#define CONST_CAST2(TOTYPE,FROMTYPE,X) ((TOTYPE)(FROMTYPE)(X))
1106#endif
1107#endif
1108#define CONST_CAST(TYPE,X) CONST_CAST2 (TYPE, const TYPE, (X))
1109#define CONST_CAST_TREE(X) CONST_CAST (union tree_node *, (X))
1110#define CONST_CAST_RTX(X) CONST_CAST (struct rtx_def *, (X))
1111#define CONST_CAST_RTX_INSN(X) CONST_CAST (struct rtx_insn *, (X))
1112#define CONST_CAST_BB(X) CONST_CAST (struct basic_block_def *, (X))
1113#define CONST_CAST_GIMPLE(X) CONST_CAST (gimple *, (X))
